            section
                h2 Research 

                p The long-term view of this would be an item that would eventually take on a more interactive approach to the information that was delivered. I had started by looking at interactive story-telling techniques. Naturally, I came across the New York Times interactive stories - while this project wasn’t going to accomplish this yet, it was good to think how this project could eventually evolve into that. 

                p I looked around at how news agencies and blogs delivery their information, what were consistencies across the board and what leeway did I have as a designer to make this our own. 

                p I also looked back at all of the Agroforestry Notes from the 90s and looked at how the publication series itself evolved. I thought about what I could keep that maintained the recognition.

                p The department has a Design Standards document that I looked through to see if anything needed to be implemented into the new design. 

            section
                h2 The Journey

                p These notes were originally design to be hole-punched, stuck in a binder, and taken out to the field by resource professionals. They were black and white because it was less expensive than 4-color printing. 

                blockquote.left We were no longer bound to black and white... 
                p We decided to continue publishing online PDFs, but thought that this was a good time to consider giving this series a bit of a face-lift. 

                p We were no longer bound to black and white as the documents would be viewed digitally or printed out by the user themselves. There was no longer a need to saddle stitch, which required design the product to have pages in multiples of four.  As I designed this ‘new’ look, I went over the various elements that I could keep. I felt this would make this update feel like an extension of the series, rather than an entirely new product. 

                p Also to help update the look and feel of the publication I decided to use a more modern font. I chose Montserrat for the headings and Open Sans for the body copy. As these would be mostly digital documents. It made sense to incorporate sans-serif fonts for this project.

